### User Input in C#

C# provides the `Console` class for reading user input from the command line.

### Console.ReadLine()

Reads a line of text from the console as a string:

```csharp
Console.Write("Enter your name: ");
string name = Console.ReadLine();
Console.WriteLine($"Hello, {name}!");
```

### Reading Numbers

`Console.ReadLine()` always returns a string. Convert it to numeric types:

```csharp
Console.Write("Enter your age: ");
string input = Console.ReadLine();
int age = Convert.ToInt32(input);

// Alternative with parsing
int age = int.Parse(Console.ReadLine());
```

### Safe Input Parsing

Use `TryParse` to handle invalid input without exceptions:

```csharp
Console.Write("Enter a number: ");
if (int.TryParse(Console.ReadLine(), out int number))
{
    Console.WriteLine($"You entered: {number}");
}
else
{
    Console.WriteLine("Invalid number!");
}
```

### Console.Read() and Console.ReadKey()

| Method | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `Console.Read()` | Reads next character as int (ASCII value) |
| `Console.ReadKey()` | Reads a single key press |

```csharp
Console.Write("Press any key to continue...");
ConsoleKeyInfo key = Console.ReadKey();
Console.WriteLine($"\nYou pressed: {key.Key}");
```

### Multiple Input Values

```csharp
Console.Write("Enter two numbers (space-separated): ");
string[] parts = Console.ReadLine().Split(' ');
int a = int.Parse(parts[0]);
int b = int.Parse(parts[1]);
Console.WriteLine($"Sum: {a + b}");
```

> **Key Point:** Always validate user input. Use `TryParse()` instead of `Parse()` or `Convert` to avoid runtime exceptions when users enter invalid data.

### Console Color

```csharp
Console.ForegroundColor = ConsoleColor.Green;
Console.WriteLine("Green text");
Console.ResetColor();
```

codeExample:
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        Console.Write("What is your name? ");
        string name = Console.ReadLine();

        Console.Write("How old are you? ");
        if (int.TryParse(Console.ReadLine(), out int age))
        {
            Console.WriteLine($"Hello {name}, you are {age} years old.");
            Console.WriteLine($"Next year you will be {age + 1}.");
        }
        else
        {
            Console.WriteLine($"Hello {name}, nice to meet you!");
        }
    }
}
